                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d393">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/9125: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Josselyn</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-08-09T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 9, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s July 31, 1 p.m.,<note n="74" xml:id="d393fn74">Not printed.</note>
                    and your August 7, 10 a.m. Can you confirm press reports to the effect that
                    Japanese military and civilian residents at Hankow have now almost completely
                    evacuated the Japanese Concession; that the administration of the Japanese
                    Concession has been turned over temporarily to Chinese officials; and that the
                    Communist army is moving out of Shensi into Suiyuan?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
